===Etymology===
From {{der|en|ga|bean sí}}, from {{der|en|sga|ben síde||lit=woman of the fairy mound}}. The term {{m|en||banshee}} entered English in 1771.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en-us-banshee.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}
* {{IPA|/bænˈʃiː/|/ˈbænʃiː/|lang=en}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|Irish [[folklore]]}} A female [[spirit]], usually taking the form of a woman whose [[mournful]] [[wailing]] warns of an [[impend]]ing death.
# {{lb|en|derogatory}} A [[noisy]] or ill-tempered [[woman]].
#* {{quote-book|lang=en|year=1936|author=[[w:John T. McIntyre|John Thomas McIntyre]]|title=Steps Going Down|page=15|passage=Where's this old '''banshee''' that runs the place?}}

====Usage notes====
* A banshee was originally merely a [[fairy]] woman who sang a [[caoin|caoineadh]] ([[lament]]) for recently-deceased members of certain families. Translations of Irish works into English made a distinction between the banshee and other fairy folk that the original language and original stories do not seem to have, but from whence sprung the current image of the banshee.

